{"/service/ndnp/iahi/batch_iahi_frawley_ver01/data/sn88059319/00415622892/1908051901/0276.xml":{"full_text":"A\nGO\n\u00abH\na\nC5\nc3\nA Sweet\nYou Can't Beat\nLove \"snaps\" and ginger bread?\nThey're best when made with\nmco\ncom\n\"Black Hand\" Marks Hetty Green?\nNew York, May 13.\u2014Reports, which\nthose responsible for them assert are\nauthentic, are to the effect that Mrs.\nHetty Green, who is occupying apart\nments at the Plaza hotel, recently re\nceived a \"black hand\" letter threat\nening her with death unless she gave\n$5,000 to the writer.\nMakes Liquor His Theme.\nBaton Rouge, La., May 13.\u2014In the\nmessage of Qov. Blanchard sent to the\ngeneral' assembly of Louisiana Tues\nday he urges the strict regulation of\nthe liquor traffic and says that if thlq\ngpes not correct the evils growing qu^\npf the sale of liquor there should be\na^tolute prohibition.\nSYRUP\nDelightful on bread. Best for every\nthing that's better with a syrup on.\nIn air-tight tins, SOc, 25c, 50c.\nand we have every\nthing to make a com\nplete and satisfactory\njob. Call and see us.\nP\u00ab\nc3\n\u2022\"D\nmemmm\nCORN PRODUCTS\nMFG. CO.\nAll the New Ideas in Wall Paper\nDAIID\nIt Is About\nTime to\nPaint!\n03\na\nINSIDE AND OUT\nTP, A. CLEMMER\nDENTIST\nMartin Building'\nTEETH EXTRACTED WITHOUT PAIN\nSix Hurt in Automobile Crash.\nLexington, Ky., May 13.\u2014Six per\nsons were hurt when an automobile,\nowned and driven by L. Gay Strode,\ncrashed Into a stone fence near the\ncity and a tire burst. All will recov\ner. There wore four women In the\nparty.\nMme. Gould at Monte Carlo*\nGenoa, May 13.\u2014Mme. Gould and\nher children, accompanied by Princ\nHelie de Sagan, who left Rome, ar\nrived In this city Tuesday. They had\nbreakfast in the station and left at\nonce for Monte Carlo,\noAsvonx^.,\nBern the Kind You Han Always Bouglit\nOUR STOCK OF\n:-.'S\nWall Paper\nis now complete from the very\ncheapest to the most artistic\nnew ideas in Wall Decorations.\nLet us show them to you. t.\n's Certificate\nThis wilLwitness.that\nAndrew Smith,of CrestO,%lo\\*va\nJias jaeen t|ioroug}ily schooled in the science of erect\ning Lightening kocjs according to the DODD\nST^yTHE^S \u00a7y\u00a7teqjj aiiji who i\u00a7 hereby authorized\nto countersign in the following territory, vi? Crespq\nand tributary trade, our guarantee issued for the\nprotection tf our customers-.^. 2^\u2022\nThere are flany Imitations\nof our rod on the market, but insist on getting the\ngenuine. Purchaser must see that the goods are\nmarked with our registered trade mark,\n1\nDodd Struthers, Des Moines, la.\n^i- Tunlfir in. msT^ frt7\nFurniture. Carpets and Matfnss\nUndertaking in All its Branches\nDr. John J. Clemmer\ni\u00a3\u00bb\nBy E. R. STOTTS.\nHEVERDEN\nPRICES *t\nGold Filling $1.50 up\nSilyer Filling 75c\nCement Filling 75c\nGold Crowns,,,.$5.00 up\nPorcelain Crowns $5.00\nBridge Work $5 a tooth\nPlates $7.50\nCHAPTER XXXIII.\n8 they had gathered to hear\nRalph Slade's talc, so now the\ndepleted mess of the Wolver\nine grouped themselves for\nPercy Darrow's sequel. Slade himself\nsnt directly across from the doctor's\nassistant. Before him lay a paper cov\nered with Jotted notes. Trcndon\nslouched low In the chair on Slade's\nright. Captain Parkinson had the oth\ner side. Convenient to Darrow's hand\nlay the material for cigarettes. As he\ntalked lie rolled cylinder after cylinder\nand between sentences consumed them\nin long, satisfying puffs.\n\"First you will want to learn of the\nfate of your friends and shipmates,\"\nhe began. \"They are dead. One of\nthem, Mr. Edwards, fell to my hands\nto bury, as you know. He lies beside\nHandy Solomon. The others we shall\nprobably not see. Any one of a score\nof ocean currents may have swept\nthem far away. The last great glow\nthat you saw was the signal of their\ndestruction. So the work of a great\nscientist, a potent benefactor of the\nrace, a gentle and kindly old heart, has\nbrought about the death of your friends\nand of my aneinies. The innocent\nand the guilty, the murderer with his\nplunder, the officer following his duty,\nqne and the same end\u2014a paltry thing\nPUP vaunted science 1b In the face of\nsuch tangled fates.\" He spoke low\nand bitterly. Then he squared his\nshoulders, and his manner became\nbusinesslike.\n\"Interrupt me when any point needs\nclearing up,\" he said. \"It's a blind\ntrail at best. You've the right to see it\nas plain as I can make it\u2014with Slade's\nhelp. Cut tight in with your questions.\nThere'll be plenty to answer, and some\nnever will be answered. Now, let me\nget this thing laid out clearly in my\nown mind. You first saw the glow\nlet me see\"\u2014\n\"Night of June 2,\" said Burnett.\n\"June 2,\" agreed Darrow. \"That was\nthe end of Solomon, Thrackles Co.\nA very surprising end to them if they\nhad time to think,\" he added grimly.\n\"Surprising enough from the surviv\nors' viewpoint,\" said Slade.\n\"Doubtless. They've had that story\nfrom yoh. I needn't go over it. This\nship picked up the Laughing Lass, de\nserted, and put your first crew aboard.\nThat night, was it not, you saw the\nsecond pillar of fire?\"\n0'\nBd STEWART EDWARD WHITE\nAnd SAMUEL HOPKINS ADAMS\nDarrow bowed with a suggestion of\nreverence In the slow movement of his\nhead. \"And that night\u2014or was It two\nnights later\u2014you saw the last appear\nance of the portent? Well, I shall\ncome to that. SJadfs has tqlcj you how\nthey lived on fl^e beach. With us In\nthe valley It yens differed. Almost\nfrom the first was alone. The doctor\nppgsed to be a companion. He ceased\nto be human almost. A machine, that's\nwhat he was. His one human instinct\nwas\u2014well, distrust His whole force of\nbeing was centered on his discovery. It\nwas to make him the foremost scientist\nof the world the foremost individual\nentity of his time\u2014of all time possibly.\nEven to outline It to you would take\ntoo much time. Light, heat, motive\npower in incredible degrees and under\nsuch control as has never been known.\nThese were to be the agencies at his\ncall. The push of a button, the torn\nof a screw\u2014oh, he was to be master\nof such power as no monarch ever\nwielded! Riches\u2014pshaw! Riches.were\nthe least of It.. He could create them\npractically. But they would be super\nfluous. Power! Unlimited, absolute\npower was his goal. With his eud\ngphlprc^, he cqu|(| psfqbllsb an autoc\nWPPi ft dynasty qf \u2022jplpnc^-Vhfttpver\nlie chose. Oh! It was a rich hued,\ngolden, glowing dream, a dream such\nas men's souls don't formulate tn these\nstale days\u2014not our kind of men. The\nTeutonic mysticism\u2014you understand.\nAnd It was all true. Oh, quite!\"\n\"Do you mean us to understand that\nhe had this power you describe?\" ask\ned Captain Parkinson.\n\"In his grasp. Then comes a prac\ntical gentlemim w}t^ 3 hook. A\ntpllqweu qC dpettiqs, faq/lq his way.\nfjqnfilptlgg Interests-^-yem know how it\nIs. Ono woll aimed blow from the\nmore practical dreamer and the great\ner vision passes. I'm getting ahead of\nmyself. Just a moment\"\nO I 1 9 0 7 E I I S O\n1\nBarnett nodded. sJ/v J..-2\n\"Sq your men piet the|r death- Then\ncame the second finding of the orapty\nschooner. Captain Parkinson, they\nmust liave boen brave men who faced\nthe unknown terrors of that prodigy.\"\n\"They volunteered, sir,\" said the cap\ntain, with simple pride.\nHis cigarette glowed fiercely in the\ndimness before he took up his tale\nagain.\n\"You all kqow who Dr. Schermer\nhorn' was. None of you know\u2014I don't\nknow myself, though I've been his fac\ntotum for ten years\u2014along how many\nTnrled lines of activity that mind play\nwl. Ono of then} was the secret of en\nprgy\u2014 poqcentcateq, resistless energy.\nM\u00bbu's contrivances were too puny for\nU(m. The most powerful engines he\nregarded as tops. For 0 time hifh ex\nplosives claimed bis ntteqtlou He\nwanted to harness thorn. Once ho got\nto the point of practical experiment.\nYou cau see tho ruins yet\u2014a hole In\nsouthern New Jersey. Nobody ever\nunderstood how he escaped. But there\nhe was on Ills feet across a ten foot\nfence in a plowed field\u2014yes, he ilew\nthe fence\u2014and running, running, furi\nously In the opposite direction when\nthe dust cleared away. Some one stop\nped him finally. Told him the danger\nwas over. 'Yet I will not return,' he\npaid firmly and fainted- away. That\nilsgustcd hhn with high explosives.\nThflt secrets ho jllsoftvercd he gave to\nftye government. Thpy were not with\nput value, I believe.\"\n\"They were not, Indeed,\" corroborat\ned Barnett,\n\"Next his Interest turned to the nat\nural phenomena of high energy. He\nstudied lightning in an open steel net\nwork laboratory, with fejv results save\nMMR\nilate\ni,1-.\n3\na succession of rhetfmatic attacks and\nan Improved electric interrupter, since\nadopted by one of the great telegraph\ncompanies. The former obliged him\nto stop these experiments, and the in\nvention he considered trivial. Proba\nbly the great problem of getting at the\nsecret of energy led him into his at\ntempts to study the mysterious elec\ntrical waves radiated by lightning\nflashes. At any rate, he was soon as\ndeep into the subject of electrical sci\nence as his countryman, Hertz, had\never been. He used to toll me that ho\noften wondered why ho hadn't taken\nup this line before\u2014tho world of ener\ngy he now set out to explore, waves In\nthat tremendous range between those\nwe hear and those we see. It was nat\nural that he should then come to the\nmost prominent radio-active elements,\nuranium, thorium and radium. But,\nthough his knowledge surpassed that\nof the much exploited authorities, he\nwas never satisfied with any of his rc\nBUltS.\n'Pitchblende, no!' he would ex\nclaim. 'It nas not the great power.\nThe mines are not deep enough yet I'\n\"Then suddenly the great idea that\nwas to bring him success and cost him\nhis life came to him. The bowels of\nthe earth must hold the socret. He\ntook up volcanoes. Does all this sound\nfoolish? It was not If you knew the\nman. He was a mighty enthusiast, a\nborn martyr. Not cold blooded, like the\nrest of us. The fire was In his veins.\nA light, please. Thank you.\n\"We chased volcanoes. There was\na theory under it all. He believed\nthat volcanic emanations are caused\nby a mighty and uncompreliended ener\ngy, something that achieves results\nascribable neither to explosions nor\nheat, some eternal, inner source. Ra\ndium, if you choose, only he didn't call\nit that. Radium, as known to our\nmodern scientists, he regarded as the\nharmless plaything of people with time\nhanging heavy on their hands. He\nwasn't after force in pin point quanti\nties\u2014he wanted results. Yet I believe\nthat, after all, what he sought was a\nsort of higher power of radium. The\nphenomena wero related. And he had\nsome of that concentrated essence of\npitchblende in tho chest when we start\ned. Oh, not much, say about $20,000\nworth. Maybe thirty. For use? No.\nRather for comparison, I Judge.\n\"Yes, wo phased volcanoes. I be\nearoe nspd to camping botweon sam\nple hells of all known varieties, got\nbo\nthat the fumes of a sulphur match\nBeemed like a draft of pure, fresh\nair. Wherever any of the earth's pim\nples showed signs of coming to a head\nthere were we, taking part In the\ntrouble. By and by the doctor got so\nthoroughly poisoned that he had to\nlay off. Back to Philadelphia we came.\nThere an aged seafaring person, tem\nporarily stranded, mulcted the profess\nor of a dollar\u2014an undertaking thnt re\nquired no art\u2014and in the course of his\nrecital touched upon yonder little cess\npool of Infernal Iniquities. An un\ncharted volcanic Island\u2014one that he\ncould havo all for his own. You may\nguess whether Dr. Schermerhom was\nInterested.\n'That iss for which we haf so long\nIn vain sought, Tercy,' he said to me\nin his quaint link chain style of\nspeech. 'A leedle prlfate volcano labo\nratory to ourselves to have. Totally\nunknown, undescrlbed, not on the\nchart to be found. Tomorrow we 6tart\nI make a list of the things to get.'\n\"He began his list, as I remember,\nwith three dozen undershirts, a gallon\nof pennyroyal for insect bites, a box of\nassorted fishhooks, thirty pounds of\ntea and a case of carpet tacks. When\nI hadn't anything else to worry over, I\nused to lie awake 'at night and specu-\non the purpose of those carpet\nacfcs. He had sonjffttyng |u mind. If\n\u00a3ere was anything fin whjph ho prid\npq himself, it was his practical bent.\nthe Ust never got any further, it\nceased short of one page lu tho ledger,\nft# you may have noticed. I outfitted\nby telegraph on the way across the\ncontinent.\n\"The doctor didn't ask me whether\nI'd go. He took it for granted. That's\nprobably why I didn't back out. Nor\ndid I tell him that tho three life insur\nance companies which had foolishly\nand trustingly accepted me as a risk\npurely pfl the strength of a good con\nstftntioq were mafelng frantic efforts\nto Compromise- on tho policies. They\nfelt hurt, those companies. My\nhealthy condition had ceased to ap\npeal to them. What's a good constitu\ntion between earthquakes? No, there\nwas no use telling the doctor. It\nwould only have worried mm. Be\nsides, I didn't helieve that the Island\nW-8B there. I thought It was a myth of\nthat stranded ancient mariner's Imag\nination. When it rose to sight at the\nproper spot, none were more astound\ned than the bad risk who now address\u00ad\nee ypu.\n\"Vflt must say f-ar. the Jslqnd that\nit pame handsomely up to specifica\ntfons. pown where yoq were, Slade,\nyou didn't get a real Insight into its\ndisposition. But In back of us there\nwas any kind of action for your mon\ney\u2014 geysers, hell spouts, fuming fis\nsures, cunning little cratorlets with\nhalf portions of molten lava ready fo\nserve hot, more gases than you could\ncreate in all the world's chemical labo\nratories\u2014in fact, everything to make\nthe place a paradise for Old Nick and\nDr. Schermerhorn. He brought along\nin his precious chest besides the ra\ndium some sort of raw material also\nas near as I could make out a sort of\nfage or guurdjanshlp scheme for ftls\nfoncgntrat^ pssencet qf cussednesq\n^heq he. should get it out 0/ tl^e vqV\npano.\n\"I13 the prst seven iponths he put\ntered arqupd the Httlo fupiers, with an\npccaslonal excursion up to the main\ncrater. It was my duty to follow\noh\nand drag lUm away when he fell un\nconscious. Sometimes I would try to\nget 14111 before ho was quite gone,\nThen he .WPUld Jaecomo Indignant ^nd\nlight me. Perhaps that helped to lose\nme his.confidence. More and more he\nwithdrew into himself. There were\ndays when lie spoke no word to me. It\nwas lonely. Do you know why I used\nto visit -you at the beach, Slade? I\nsuppose you thought I was keeping\nwatch on you. It wasn't that It wns\nloneliness. In way It hurt me, too,\nfor one couldn't help but be fond of\nthe old boy. and at times it seemed\nas if I10 weren't quite himself. Par\ndon me if I may trouble-yon for the\nmatches. Thanks.\n\"Matters went very wrong at times.\nThe doctor fumed like ills little craters,\ngrowled out long winded, exhaustive\nGerman imprecations wouldn't even\ncat. Then. aKaiii, the demon of work\nwould drive him with thong and spur\nlie would rush to his craters, to his\nlaboratories, to his ledger, for the pur\npose of entering unintelligible com\nmentaries. lie had some peculiar con\ntrivance, like a misshapen retort, with\nwhich he collected ^ases from the cra\nterlets. Whenever I'd hear one of\nthose smash I knew it was a bad day.\nMeantime the volcano also became\u2014\nwell, what you might call tempera\nmental.\n\"It got to bo a year and a quarter\u2014\na year and a half. I wondered whether\nwe should ever got away. My tobacco\nwas running short, and tho bearing of\nthe men was becoming fidgety. My\nvisits to tho beach became quite inter\nesting\u2014to me. One day the doctor\ncame running out of his laboratory\nwith so bright a face that I ventured\nto ask him about departure.\n'Not so long now, Percy,' he said In\nhis old, kind manner. 'Not so long.\nThe first real success. It iss made. We\nhave yet under entire control to bring\nit but it Iss made.'\n'And about time, sir,' said I. *If\nwe don't do something soon we may\nhave trouble with the men.'\n1\n'So?' said he In surprise. 'But they\ncould do nothing\u2014nothing.' He wag\nged his great head confidently. 'We are\narmed.'\n'Oh yes, nrmed. So are they.'\n'We are armed,' he repeated ob\nstinately. 'Such as uo man was ever\narmed are we armed.'\n\"lie checked himself abruptly and\nwalked away. Well. I've since won\ndered \u2022what would have happened had\ntho men attacked us. It would have\nbeen worth seeing ami\u2014and surprising.\nYes I'm quite certain it would have\nbeen surprising. Perhaps, too, 1 mlvrlit\nhave learned more of the groat secret\nand yet I don't know. It's all dark\u2014a\nhint here, theory, mere glints of light.\nWhere did 1 put\u2014 Ah. thank you!\"\n(To be continued)\nCHIEF TO AID ASSOCIATION\nROOSEVELT PROMISES TO SEND\nASSISTANCE.\nNational Prosperity Association Call*\non President at Washington\nExecutive Is Cordial.\nWashington, May 12.\u2014A committee\nfrom the National Prosperity associa\ntion of St. Louis called on President\nRoosevelt Monday to urge his aid in\nfurthering their plans for encourag\ning the return of prosperity through\nout U16 country. The committee found\nthe president cordial In his treatment\nand frank in his expressions of will\ningness to aid them in every way pos\nsible. A short speech was made by\np.. 0, Simmons, chairman of the ex\necutive committee of the association,\nwhich was responded to by the presi\ndent. Other members of the com\nmittee were: F. J. Wade, Edward De\nvoy, F. B. Wiberg, J. E. Smith, W. K.\nBixby, Murray Carleton, George A.\nMeyer and Jackson Johnson. Mr. Sim\nmons spoke and the president re\nsponded as follows: \"I am in hearty\nsympathy with the avowed object of\nthe National Prosperity association. It\nIs excellent. We have gone far in\nuprooting abuses which threaten our\nnational life. Taken as a whole, the\nstandard of honesty In our business\nlife has been high, and to-day the\nstandard is, I believe, beyond vrt^t it\nhas ever tysen., ^d Iqrgety ty*\ncause Save qjada d^teronlA&d\nthft souses that lowered it. Ai\nYQU said, the depression and\n^t^snatioft from which our country is\nhow\nhappily beginning to recover,\nwere not caused by reform legislation,\nbut by the revelation of shocking con\nditions in certain of our corporations,\nby reckless operations In high finance,\nby calamity, and Dy certain striking,\nthough, I believe, exceptional. In\nstances of business and civic dishon\nesty. Of course all good men must\nagree with you In your condemnation\nof unwise agitata. The apathetic\nacceptance of abuses in our govern\nmental and business administrations\nno more dangerous than the dema\ngoglo appeals of professional agitators\nto class hatreds. Our national con\nscience, I firmly believe, has been\nawakened. We will not and cannot\ngo back to the conditions which tol\nerated wrong-doing. Neither can we\naifo^d to be Jed astray by those who\nwuld embark us in a visionary and\ntwisted crusade against all corpora\ntions, all business methods. We should\naddress ourselves to the falthfuj a\u00abJ\nhonest observance of the laws of civ\nic righteousness. The welfare of al(\ncan hest be obtained by striving\nfor. a policy which will promote th\u00ab\nWelfare ol each of us, We must all\nCQhQperate In order that benefit may\nbe delved by the entire nation,\"\nSOLDIER SLAYS HIS COMRADES.\nPrivate Runs Amuck, Bullets Proving\nFatal to Four Cavalrymen.\nManila, May 12.\u2014A telegram re\nceived by the adjutant general an\nnounced that Private Mike Beacham\nof the First United States cavalry rai\\\namuck, killing three ancj pounding\nthree of his comrades, one mortally.\nThe deafl First Sergt. William\nIJoey, Private G. Wilson, Private\nThomas Woodward. Fatally wound,\ned: Private Edward Woodward. A\u00ab\nthe W.lled and wounded were members\nTroop First cavalry. Details of\nthe tragedy are lacking, but it Is pre\nsumed that Beacham was insane\nwhen he committed the deed.\nOASTORIA.\nBean the\nKl[l1\nSignature\nof\nYou Have Always Bougtf\nPrimary Ballots All 8ame Size.\nDes Moines.\u2014Attorney General By\ners has decided that the primary bal\nlots of all of the parties must be of\nthe same size, despite the fact that\nIn some counties most of the ballots\nwill be blank white paper.\nIt is not for the county auditor to\ndecide whether socialists, or prohibi\ntionists, or any other party man will\nwant to vote for the nomination\npersons for office, even if no candi\ndate's name appears on the ballot.\nGeneral Byers said In an opinion\ndirected to Secretary of State Hay\nward, responding to inquiries from\nAuditor Frank Leedham of Clinton\ncounty and others\n\"Section 1087\u2014al3 provides that\nthe ballots shall be made up of 'sep\narate sheets of paper uniform in\ncolor, quality, texture and size.' To\nfully meet this provision of the law\nmy judgment is, that the ballots for\nall parties should be of the same\nsize, and that in preparing them the\nauditor should have printed on each\nballot squares and blank spaces for\nall offices to be voted for at the prim\nary for which no nomination papers\nor affidavits have been filed.\"\nThe attorney general holds that \"it\nis evident from the provisions that\nit was not Intended by the legislature\nthat candidates for delegates to coun\nty conventions and for precinct com\nmitteemen should file affidavits as\nprovided in section 1087-al0 of the\nprimary law. In fact, this section\nmakes it clear that it is only candi\ndates for elective offices who are re\nquired to file such affidavits.\nk-\nTwo More Conventions.\nThe Iowa Grain Dealers' associa\ntion will hold its annual convention\nin this city July 14. About 800 grain\ndealers will attend the meeting. The\nannual state convention of the Ep\nworth league will be held in Des\nMoines during September, the date\nndt yet having been fully decided\nupen. It is expected that more than\n4,000 members of various branches of\nthe Epworth league from all parts\nof the state will be in Des Moines to\nattend the annual meeting.\nDES MOINES LETTER\nPharmacy Examinations.\nFred Russell of Calhoun county has\nbeen elected chairman of the state\nboard of pharmacy, according to the\nrule of rotation among the members.\nCharles J. Phillips was elected secre\ntary of the board. It was decided to\nhold the next examination of appli\ncants for certificates on June 3 and a\nspecial examination was fixed fo?\nJune 15 at Iowa City specially for\nthe benefit ?f the graduates of the\nuniversity and for others wish\nto take it at that time,\nInterstate License System.\nAn interstate icense system for\nphysicians will be one of the things\nto be discussed at the state medical\nmeeting to be held In Des Moines\nMay 20. The physicians maintain\nthat all accredited physicians should\nbe listed and not be subjected to an\nother examination and registry when\nthey enter another state. A Confer\nence has been called for May 19 of\nthe physicians and health officers of\nthe state to discuss legislative meas\nures desired from the next general\nassembly,\nItems of Interest From Our Correspondent\nat the State Capital.\nEvery Wotnau Will Ite Interested.\nIf you have pains in the back, Uri\nnary, Bladderor Kidney trouble, and\nwant a certain, pleasant herb cure for\nwoman's ills, try Mother Gray's Aus\ntralian Leap, It is a safe and never\nfailing regulator. At Druggists or by\nmail 50 cts. Sample package FREE.\nAddress, The Mother Gray Co., LeRov.\nN. Y. 72w4\nFeel languid, weak, run-down? Head\nache? Stomach \"off\"?\u2014Just a plain\ncase of lazy liver. Burdock Blood Bit\nters tones the liver and stomach, pro\nmotes digestion, purifies the blood.\nt.- g^'\"\"\nrSSr?\nI-?*\n\"There is no provision in the prim\nary law authorizing the auditor to\nhave printed upon the primary ballot\nthe names of candidates for either\ndelegates to county conventions or\nprecinct committeemen: In fact, the\nlaw specifically provides that the\nnames of the candidates for such po\nsitions must be 'written or pasted with\nuniform white pasters on the blank\nlines upon the ballot by the voter\nwhile in the booth,' etc.\"\nWhere no candidate is proposed by\nthe filing of nomination papers or\naffidavit with the auditor for some of\nthe offices for which nominations are\nto be made at the primary, and the\nballot is prepared with blank spaces\nas shown In the form of ballot set\nout in seotion 1087-al4 of the supple\nment to the code, the attorney gen\neral was asked if the voters affiliated\nwith the party whose ballots is so\nmade up, can write in the name of the\nperson of their choice, put a cross in\nthe square opposite the name so writ\nten, and in that manner make nomi\nnations. He replied:\n\"Section 1087-a6 of the primary\nact, among other things provides that\nthe Australian- ballot system shall\nbe used at the primary election, and\nmakes certain provisions with refer\nence to the manner In which votes\nfor persons whose name is written\nupon the ballot by the voter shall be\ncounted. Section 1119 of chapter 3,\ntitle 6, of the code, which by the prim\nary act is made applicable to prim\nary elections, provides among other\nthings that 'the voter may also in\nsert in writing in the proper place\nthe name of any person for whom he\ndesires to vote, making a cross op\nposite thereto.\" These provisions\nput is beyond doubt that the voters\nat the primary may write ip the\nnames of the candidate^ of their\nohoice and mafc$ nominations in that\nway.\".\nGeological Report Is IssuecL\nThe fact that three cement com*\npanles have been organized in Iowa,\nand that one has Installed a $2,000,*\n000 plant, and begun production, lends\nspecial interest to the new volume of\nthe reports of the Iowa geological\nsurvey. No. 17 having just been is\nsued. The volume is devoted to the\nquarry industry of the state. The\ndiscussion of the main topic is pre*\nceded by the annual reports of the\ndirector. Dr. Samuel Calvin, and of\nthe assistant director, James H. Lees.\nAccompanying these reports is a two\npage map of Iowa showing the differ\nent geological formations of the state.\nProfessor Beyer of Ames contri\nbutes a report on the economic pos\nsibilities of the different geological\nformations, and this deals first with\nthe materials and manufacture of\nPortland cement. This article treats\nof the different classes of cements\nand their qualities, the materials\nused in making Portland cement, the\nfactors determining the value of these\nmaterials, the methods of manufac\nture and the testing of raw materials\nto determine their availability for\nmanufacture of Portland cement.\nNext the report discusses the physi\ncal tests of Iowa limes, the different\nclasses of lime and their peculiar\ncharacter, the qualities of limes and\nlime mortars, and gives an elaborate\nseries of tests of typical limes from\nIowa kilns, including tnose at Mason\nCity, Eagle Point, Dubuque, Maquo\nketa and Viola.\nProf. G. W. Blssell, formerly of Iowa\nState college, has contributed a valu\nable article on the selection of power\nplants and equipment for stone quar\nries in Iowa. He gives the requisites\nfor boilers, feedwater heaters, en\ngines, etc., and adds a useful dis\ncussion of the properties of Iowa\ncoals and their analysis, methods of\nfiring and cost of fuel and of steam.\nHe further discusses the use of the\ngas engine, as used under normal con\nditions.\nThe larger part of the report Is\noccupied by the treatment of the\ngeology of quarry products and gives\nthe resources of each county in de\ntail.\nResults on State's Farms.\nJohn Cownie has decided hereafter\nto fix the salaries of the farmers who\nhave charge of the state land at the\nInstitutions according to results that\nthey obtain.\nIn a letter sent out to them he has\ntold them that that Is his intention.\nHe expects that there will not only be\nresults on the farms but results from\nthe letter. He has said to the farm\ners\n\"I expect to take an Inventory of\nall of our com fields at our state In\nstitutions during the suaimer and will\nmake a report of the conditions as\nthey actually exist, a copy being fur\nnished each Institution, and we then\ncan determine at which institution the\nwork is done the best. Tho salaries\nof our farmers should be fixed in ac\ncordance with the results obtained.\"\nInasmuch as the state of Iowa is\nthe biggest farmer In the state\u2014\noperating every year about 20,000\nacres of land\u2014the decision of the\nboard of control as announced by\nChairman Cownie is of much interest.\nProhibitionists are Coming.\nifT y,.\n1\nThe national committee of the\nAmerican Anti-Saloon league has\ngiven the central district anti-saloon\nconvention to Iowa, the meeting to he\nheld In Des Moines in September.\nThe district embraces ten states, In\ncluding North and South Dakota,,\nNebraska, Kansas, Oklahoma, Minne-'\nsota, Iowa, Missouri Wisconsin and\nIllinois.\nThe convention will bring 400 su\nperintendents and workers to Des\nMoines and will continue in session\nfor ten days, continuing over Sunday.\nThis Sunday will be known as resub\nmission day in Iowa and the 400 su\nperintendents and workers will be\nsent over Iowa to fill church pulpits\nfor this cause. It will also be known\nas resubmission day in Des Moines\nwith the local pulpits filled by dis\ntrict superintendents. It is expected\nthat the evening meetings will be\npopular sessions while the business\nsession will be held in the day meet\ning-\nCosson Resigns Position.''\nAssistant Attorney General George^\nCosson has resigned his place with\nAttorney General Byers at the state\nhouse. He Is a candidate for the re\npublican nomination for state senator\nin the Audubon-Dallas-Guthrle dis\ntrict, formerly represented by Senator\nHopkins of Guthrie county and Sena\ntor Hotchklss of Dallas county.\nft,\"!- 1 \u2022..-A\n4\n-iy -ii\nPrisoner Escapes.\nTaking advantage of the crowded\ncondition of the court house winding\nstairs, Harry Cameron, one of th^\nthirteen prisoners taken to the court\nhouse to challenge the grand jury\neluded the deputy sheriffs and lost\nhimself in the crowd. Cameron es\ncaped when the prisoners were being\ntaken from the court room to tha\npatrol wagon outside which was wait\ning to take them to the county jail.\nHis escape was not noticed u&til\nthe jail was reached.\nThe World's Best Climate\nis not entirely free from diseases, on\nthe high elevations fevers prevail, while\non the lower levels malaria is encount\nered to a greater or less extent, accord\ning to altitude. To overcome climate\naffections lassitude, malaria, jaundice,\nbiliousness, fever and ague, and gen\neral debility, the most effective remedy jf-r\nis Electric Bitters, the alternative and\nblood purifier the antidote for every\nform of bodily weakness, nervousness,\nand insomnia. Sold under guarantee\nat P. A. Clemmer's drug store. Price\n50 cents.\nvV","height":"28824","width":"21276"}}
